So we found the "China Town" of Richardson, and we've been going there a lot for groceries. It's pretty awesome and they have Bubba Tea/Tapioca tea.

ALSO, this morning, one of my roommates, Whitley, left a pan of oil on the stove and ended up setting off the smoke detectors. Thus I woke up to smoke and loud beeping sounds when I actually wanted to sleepin today. But I went outside to play some volleyball and it was all good.
Then I went over to Stephen and Steve's apartment and they made oatmeal pancakes and watched Water World [possibly one word]. Pretty awesome.

Tonight's agenda: study for Government and French exams. Bake cookies with Amanda. Find boxes to mail things in. Write thank you notes??

It's almost nauseating how much I miss people sometimes, but I must prepare for my coming French class (at 5:30). I love my roommates and the people I've met and the weather here is absolutely insane, but I can't wait for winter break and this long weekend. This is it for now! Love--

I get emailed every day by "Doctor Dictionary" and he sends me "the Word of the Day" which two days ago happened to be this weird LATIN thing. I saw the word and I said "what now?" because that's what it meant literally, and I thought wow, I say that phrase a lot sometimes. I should start saying it in latin.

quidnunc \KWID-nuhngk\, noun:
   One  who  is  curious  to know everything that passes; one who knows  or  pretends  to know all that is going on; a gossip; a busybody.

Not to mention the fact that you pronouce it KWIDnuhngk. -fin-

I don't think I can go see Sara, Mere and Nick at the airport tonight . . . I have a complicated mix of feelings about it, mostly regret, but also a sense of spite. That's not good (the spite I mean, but regret too), but I can't help it if I can only grit my teeth at the injustices of this world, and let fate unroll itself. If it has to unroll in this way, at least it brings the same punishment to all involved. That's not very nice, so maybe I'll repent later as hot tears spring forth a foggy reason shrouds itself in those clouds of cotton candy. the indescribable way that nerves shoot voltage up my spine, and fill me with this cold awe at the wonders of energy. Dog ho!* jupiter on earth. *reference to The Poisonwood Bible which I finished yesterday I looked at the mood to make sure I spelled "indescribable" right.

HOLY CRAP I was downloading at 103kB/sec. Yeah, I just wanted everyone to know. This is most definetly not directed toward someone; it just cracked me up. If you go to Japan, visit a karaoke ba (bahh; bar) at least once and sing while you drink. Check the index of kyoku (kyoh-koo; musical pieces) and ask for the song that you want to utau (oo-tah-oo; sing). When it's your ban (bahn; turn), sing into the maiku (mah-ee-koo; microphone) as you watch the kashi (kah-shee; lyrics) scroll across the gamen (gah-mehn; monitor). Sing like a suta (soo-tahh; star), even if you're onchi (ohn-chee; tone-deaf). -Japanese for Dummies and yes, I am an official Dummie. On the topic of summer break . . . I'm really going to miss everyone a lot. It's not just that I'm not doing anything interesting, but I really love seeing everyone (or mostly everyone) every day at school. But it'd definetly be not as horrible if I was going to Japan or something. <3

I knew it all along. <3 So I was thinking about writing an entry some time soon . . . and then I thought nah, most people know what's going on in my life, because there isn't much going on in my life . . . I don't really understand it all either . . . sometimes I don't even feel like I'm living. I don't know if I've ever really lived in my life . . . true, I can't remember most of my earlier childhood, and banging my head on the tree yesterday morning probably didn't help much, but these days, these routine, mundane, trite, boring, repetitive school days are really bothering the philosophical me (if any of you believe that I have one anyway). Over spring break, or rather in the first few days of it, I read all of Thornton Wilder's The Bridge of San Luis Rey and loved almost every bit of it. Yes, sometimes it was rather boring, but Wilder's language was absolutely exquisite, and the themes of his novella are amazingly complex. The very last sentences of his book were quoted by Tony Blair at the memorial service for the 9/11 attack, and I am at a lack of words to describe them and their beauty. Everyone should read it, or at least the foreword written by Russell Banks (which basically summarizes the book and its motifs). If anyone actually reads this all, I commend you (and scoff at Max who said that no one would be stupid enough to want to read it or something along those lines). I think I used enough big words and fancy language for one day. Time for chemistry! -out-
